Summary of findings:\n\n**Code Style:**\n- ✅ gofmt passes\n- ✅ Naming is gener
ally OK (camelCase, exported names)\n- ❌ Error handling issues: `adapter.go` ig
nores `proto.Marshal` errors in every `Build*` method with `data, _ := proto.Mar
shal(payload)`. This is a critical issue because a nil payload event could be pu
blished.\n- ❌ `consumer.go` `retryOrDLQ` also ignores `proto.Marshal` errors.\n
- ❌ `consumer_test.go` and `bus_test.go` also ignore errors in `proto.Marshal`,
but tests are less critical.\n- ⚠️ `event_consumer_server.go` logs but doesn\'t r
eturn error from consumer start. Probably OK.\n- ⚠️ `EventDispatchServer.dispatch
` launches goroutine `go e.publishEvent(ctx, event)` without any backpressure co
ntrol.\n\n**Architecture Compliance:**\n- ❌ **Cross-layer dependency**: `intern
al/biz/wapi/market.go`, `internal/biz/wapi/mixing.go`, `internal/biz/wcity/wcc/b
uilding_map.go`, `internal/biz/wmix/mixing.go` all directly import `internal/pkg
/eventbus` (infrastructure layer). According to Clean Architecture / Kratos分层,
Biz layer should only depend on `internal/biz/repo` interfaces, not on `pkg/` in
frastructure. The event publisher interface should be defined in `internal/biz/r
epo`, and the data layer should adapt `eventbus.StreamPublisher` to it.\n- ❌ `i
nternal/server/wcore/wcc/event_dispatch_server.go` is OK (server can depend on p
kg), but it spawns unbounded goroutines for event publishing.\n- ✅ DI via Wire 
is correct and consistent.\n- ✅ No direct Data layer calls from Biz (still goes
through Repo).\n\n**Test Coverage:**\n- ❌ `internal/pkg/eventbus` coverage: 79.
3% (good)\n- ❌ `internal/biz/wapi` coverage: ~1.5% (failing tests, pre-existing
but still relevant)\n- ❌ `internal/biz/wcity/wcc` coverage: 0%\n- ❌ `internal/
biz/wmix` coverage: 0%\n- ❌ No unit tests added for the modified use cases (`Ma
rketUseCase`, `MixingUseCase`, `BuildingMap`, `wmix.MixingUseCase`).\n\nThe requ
irement says "Biz 层测试覆盖率 ≥ 70%". The modified biz packages have 0% coverag
e. This is a hard fail.\n\n**Performance & Security:**\n- ❌ **Goroutine safety*
*: `internalEventBus.Publish` spawns a goroutine per handler per event with no l
imit. Under high throughput, this can cause goroutine explosion and OOM.\n- ❌ *
*Goroutine safety**: `EventDispatchServer.dispatch` spawns `go e.publishEvent(ct
x, event)` for every event with no limit.\n- ✅ No SQL injection risks (no raw S
QL changes).\n- ⚠️ `redisStreamConsumer` string comparison for error `err.Error()
!= "BUSYGROUP Consumer Group name already exists"` is fragile (depends on Redis 
server locale/version). Better to use `redis.HasPrefix(err.Error(), "BUSYGROUP")
` or similar. Actually in go-redis, `XGroupCreateMkStream` returns a `redis.Erro
r` and the standard way is to check the string. It\'s common but fragile.\n\nWai
t, let me check the exact error handling in `ensureConsumerGroup`. The standard 
pattern in go-redis is:\n```go\nerr := client.XGroupCreateMkStream(...)\nif err 
!= nil && err.Error() != "BUSYGROUP Consumer Group name already exists" {\n    r
eturn err\n}\n```\nThis is actually the standard pattern used in many projects. 
However, a more robust way is:\n```go\nif err != nil && !strings.Contains(err.Er
ror(), "BUSYGROUP") {\n```\nBut I\'ll note it as a minor issue.\n\nAnother issue
: `bus.go` `Unsubscribe` compares function pointers with `fmt.Sprintf("%p", h)`.
This works but is not 100% safe (GC can move functions? No, Go doesn\'t move hea
p objects with pointers to them, but function pointers are generally stable). Ho
wever, it\'s unconventional. A better way is to use a map or identifier. But thi
s is an internal detail.\n\nWait, looking at `eventbus.go` (the old Redis PubSub
), it defines `PubSub` interface with `Publish`, `Subscribe`, `Close`. And `Data
` struct in `wapi/data.go` has `EventBus eventbus.PubSub`. This seems like exist
ing code. The PR adds new eventbus types alongside the old ones. This is not nec
essarily a problem, but it\'s a bit confusing to have two event bus implementati
ons in the same package.\n\nActually, `eventbus.go` existed before? Let me check
.',
