nd check for issues like ignoring errors in `proto.Marshal`.\n\nAlso, I noticed 
in `internal/pkg/eventbus/adapter.go`, all the `Build*` methods ignore `proto.Ma
rshal` errors:\n```go\ndata, _ := proto.Marshal(payload)\n```\n\nThis is a serio
us issue - if marshaling fails, `data` could be nil and the event will have an e
mpty payload. Error should be handled.\n\nIn `consumer.go`, `retryOrDLQ` also ig
nores proto.Marshal errors:\n```go\ndata, _ := proto.Marshal(event)\n```\n\nAnd 
in `bus_test.go` and `consumer_test.go`, there are also `data, _ := proto.Marsha
l(...)` but that\'s in tests, which is less critical but still not ideal.\n\nIn 
`event_consumer_server.go`, the `Start` method launches `s.consumer.Start(ctx)` 
in a goroutine but returns immediately. If `Start` fails immediately, the error 
is only logged. That\'s probably OK since it\'s a background server.\n\nBut ther
e are more issues:\n1. `EventDispatchServer.dispatch` spawns `go e.publishEvent(
ctx, event)` for every event. This could lead to goroutine explosion under high 
load since there\'s no rate limiting or worker pool for publishing.\n2. `interna
lEventBus.Publish` also spawns a goroutine per handler per event. If there are m
any events, this could cause goroutine leaks or excessive memory usage. However,
the handlers are expected to be quick.\n3. In `EventDispatchServer.publishEvent`
, there\'s a race condition or data race potential? No, `eventAdp` is read-only 
after construction.\n4. `EventConsumerServer.Start` returns immediately but the 
consumer is started in a goroutine. The `kratos.App` lifecycle expects `Start` t
o block or at least be synchronous for initialization. However, since `StreamCon
sumer.Start` is blocking, wrapping it in a goroutine is correct.\n5. `redisStrea
mConsumer.Start` waits for all partition consumers with `wg.Wait()`. But `EventC
onsumerServer.Start` launches it in a goroutine. So the app start won\'t block. 
This is fine.\n\nArchitecture issues:\n- Biz layer directly imports `internal/pk
g/eventbus`. This violates Clean Architecture principles (Biz should not depend 
